<HL>
   Sounds Like a Good Way to Have
   Modern Art Reflect Modern Life
   ----
   By Suzanne Alexander
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Some folks think modern art is rubbish. Susan Pedicord, on
the other hand, thinks modern rubbish should be art.
   In an effort to improve the environment -- and perhaps
nurture budding Picassos -- Ms. Pedicord has opened a store
in Montpelier, Vt., to recycle trash as art supplies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Appropriately named "Restore," the shop offers everything
from discarded legal pads, partly used wallpaper rolls and
pillow stuffing to clothespin springs, red plastic bottle
caps and wood chips. Customers -- mostly artists, parents and
kids -- use the materials for such arts and crafts as
collages, sculptures, mobiles and toys. Teachers also load up
on supplies for use in art classes.
   "Most of the materials are perfectly good. They have one
little scratch or wrinkle, and they're no longer useful to a
company," says Ms. Pedicord. An artist herself, she came up
with the idea for Restore three years ago after hoarding
leftover scraps from an art project.
   Since then, she has persuaded 100 Vermont businesses to
channel their scraps to Restore instead of burdening
landfills. "Our environmental goal is to get waste out of the
waste stream," says Ms. Pedicord. She spends much of her time
driving from bottle makers to brush makers to quilt makers --
loading up her small pickup truck with their rubbish. And she
also approaches new companies, touring their facilities in
search of usable waste.
   Vermont artists and kids love the store -- especially the
prices. On opening day this month, more than 200 people
showed up. At 10-for-a-penny, mailing labels and promotional
stickers were among the hot items. "Kids love stickers,"
explains Ms. Pedicord. But 1990 U.S. Census pencils were also
selling fast.
   Restore, a unit of Restore Resources Unlimited, a
nonprofit, waste-reduction organization, soon will begin
exhibiting the work of local artists who've used discarded
materials in their pieces. "We wanted to give the art
community both access to inexpensive art materials and a new
place to exhibit their work," says Ms. Pedicord. In addition,
the retailer may sponsor recycled-art competitions at several
local schools.
   Ms. Pedicord maintains that her store represents "the kind
of creative problem solving that will help solve the
environmental problems we're facing today." She doesn't
address, however, what happens when her customers throw away
their art projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900830-0144
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900830-0144.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   New Construction
   Was Down in July,
   F.W. Dodge Reports
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Another monthly decline in new construction
contracts points to still lower levels of building in the
months ahead, according to F.W. Dodge, the forecasting unit
of McGraw-Hill Inc.
   Dodge said setbacks in all segments in July resulted in an
annualized construction startup rate of $232.31 billion, down
from $244.85 billion in June. The seasonally adjusted rate
brought the Dodge index down to 148 from 156 the previous
month. The index compares current contracting with a 1982
base of 100.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "Restrictive credit, budget austerity, and a stagnant
economy are more than enough reasons for the sorry state of
construction in 1990," said George A. Christie, vice
president and chief economist for Dodge. Energy inflation is
an added impediment to improvement in the near future.
   The weakest segment, nonresidential building, dropped 8%
to $80.5 billion, as a result of lagging office construction,
which fell 23% to the lowest rate in a decade. Nonbuilding
construction, including public works and utilities, was down
7% to $42.4 billion, and homebuilding was down 2% to $109.4
billion.
   Through seven months of 1990, $143 billion of new
construction was started, 8% less than the comparable 1989
period. The most severe regional declines continued to be in
the Northeast, down 24%, and the Southeast, down 15% through
July.
