</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   TV: Top-Notch Tennis, Spiritual Cooking, Crime Prevention
   ----
   By Dorothy Rabinowitz
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<LP>
   Saturday, Sept. 1, 12:30-6 p.m. EDT, on CBS: U.S. Open
Tennis from Flushing Meadows, N.Y. Continues same times
Sunday and Monday. Friday, Sept. 7, 11 a.m.-5 p.m., women's
singles semis, men's doubles final. Saturday, 11 a.m-7 p.m.,
men's singles semis, women's singles final. Sunday, 4-7 p.m,
men's singles final.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Saturday, Sept. 1, 10:30-11 p.m. EDT, on NBC: "AFI
Presents TV or Not TV?" an American Film Institute special
hosted by Jack Lemmon and featuring skits developed at the
AFI summer workshop. The program is the work, in short, of
aspiring comedy writers, normally a prospect to make the
blood run cold. This would be no exception but for one
laceratingly clever sketch called "Cooking With God" that
makes the whole enterprise, complete with sendups of Roseanne
Barr and "Twin Peaks," seem worth enduring. "Cooking With
God" is four minutes of wildly inspired nastiness aimed at
money-hustling television ministries. Harry Shearer stars as
the Rev. Robert Tilton, author of "The Robert Tilton Blind
Faith Cookbook," which among other things implores us to
"Accept the Lord as your personal chef."
                                                                                                       

   Sunday, Sept. 9, 9-11 p.m. EDT, on HBO: "Somebody Has to
Shoot the Picture," a compelling and oddly stylish film
notwithstanding the ungainly title. Roy Scheider is at his
lachrymose best as the photographer hero drawn into the
(fictional) case of a death-row inmate facing imminent
execution despite substantial questions about his guilt. Both
a murder mystery and a raw closeup of the business of
execution, the film is unmistakably a brief against the death
penalty, but one that fortunately avoids the usual
sermonizing.
                                                                                                       

   Monday, Sept. 10, 8-10 p.m. EDT, on TNT: "The Lost
Capone." You probably didn't know Al Capone had a nice
younger brother. Well apparently he did, and TNT has
unearthed him for us, via the work of newspaper columnist
James Bacon, on whose research this quasi-biographical saga
is based. Young Jimmy Capone, it appears, shared none of the
family predilection for violence, which outraged his
soon-to-become-famous brother Al the mobster and his barber
father who was sympathetic to mobs. Young Jimmy lit out for
new territory, where, to his elderly parent's further
mortification, he became a law officer. The relatives cannot
hold their heads up for shame. Clearly this is a crime-family
version of "The Jazz Singer," wherein this youth breaks his
old father's heart by running off to become a good citizen
instead of a singer. Under the alias Richard ("Two Gun")
Hart, the wayward Capone becomes the scourge of bootleggers
out West, among them, needless to say, Brother Al. The
producers note that some aspects of this history have been
fictionalized, which is also needless to say. Eric Roberts is
a credible Al Capone, despite an Italian accent that
regularly veers off into something a lot more like a cross
between Navajo and Romanian. Nevertheless, all this is
enormously entertaining, with a noteworthy performance from
actor Titus Welliver, who extracts more from the role of
middle brother Ralph Capone than one would have thought
possible.
                                                                                                       

   Wednesday, Sept. 12, 8-9 p.m., on CBS: "Are You Safe? A
National Test on Crime Prevention." Kevin Dobson is the host
of this grimly practical compendium of pointers on ways to
avoid becoming a crime victim. It makes use, to be sure, of
test gimmickry, with answers and points scored, but there is
nothing relaxing or gamelike about this hour, which is
chillingly evocative in its portraits of the criminal
endeavor. Nothing gets one's attention more than the sight of
criminals about to pounce, and that sight, in all its hideous
variety, from street muggings to burglary to worse (all
reenactments), is what ensures that no one will fall asleep
watching this. It also is the reason a good many citizens
watching it are likely to want to go out and get a gun,
though this clearly is not the response intended by the
producers. The program underlines and amplifies the
well-justified sense now haunting everyone's life, that crime
and danger are just around the corner, waiting to strike.
This hour is, to repeat, no barrel of laughs, but it is hard
to imagine any television program that comes closer to
peoples' real concerns than these sometimes predictable,
sometimes surprising instructions on ways to stay alive.
Watch.
                                                                                                       

   Wednesday, Sept. 12, 9-10 p.m. EDT, on A&amp;E: "The 1960
National Democratic Convention." The hit of the year was
"Itsy Bitsy Teeny Weeny Yellow Polka Dot Bikini," which did
not augur well for the new decade. The 1960 Democratic
Convention, which resulted in the nomination of John F.
Kennedy, brings back a lot more of the flavor of the time. It
was one of the last conventions that could still lay claim to
the appearance of a contest, as opposed to the ceremonial
annointments of today. John Chancellor narrates this
irresistible look back at a convention in which Kennedy's
competitors were, among others, Adlai Stevenson and Lyndon B.
Johnson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900830-0116
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900830-0116.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   The Philippines
   Seeks Flexibility
   On Debt Terms
   ----
   By Lawrence MacDonald and Steven Jones
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   The Philippines, hard hit by an earthquake in July and the
current Mideast crisis, is seeking more-flexible arrangements
for repaying its $26.1 billion foreign debt.
   "There is now a greater need for debt relief," said Jose
Cuisia Jr., governor of the Central Bank of the Philippines.
"There should be greater flexibility."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Cuisia said in an interview, however, that the
administration of President Corazon Aquino will resist calls
for a moratorium on foreign-debt payments. The Philippine
Congress has passed nonbinding resolutions asking the
president to negotiate a 30-month moratorium, but Mrs. Aquino
says she will veto any bill requiring a payment halt, which
could ruin the country's international credit rating and
hinder foreign trade and investment.
   A series of debt-rescheduling agreements has extended
repayment periods, but the country's debt burden remains
heavy. This year, for instance, payments will eat up 40% of
the national budget. One-third of those payments go to
foreign creditors.
   As an example of the flexibility he is seeking from
creditors, Mr. Cuisia said the Philippines wants to conduct
another buy-back of commercial-bank debt this year, similar
to the $1.31 billion buy-back completed in January. To do so,
the government will need permission of the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank to use funds lent by those
institutions.
   Under a 1989 debt-restructuring agreement, commercial-bank
creditors have been given a choice of offering debt to the
government for repurchase or of subscribing to new 15-year
Philippine bonds. Earlier this year, the Philippines sold
more than $700 million of bonds to creditor banks, an amount
lower than the government had expected.
   Mr. Cuisia said another buy-back would be the "most
cost-effective" way for the country to reduce its debt
burden. Many foreign commercial banks also favor such action
as a way to remove Philippine debt from their books, even at
a discount. In the January buy-back, the government
repurchased bank debt at 52 cents for every $1 of existing
debt with funds from the IMF, World Bank and Japan's
Export-Import Bank.
   Mr. Cuisia said the amount of commercial-bank debt
tendered in the January buy-back exceeded the $1.31 billion
actually retired, and he suggested there is at least $500
million and probably $800 million to $1 billion more of debt
that could be retired through another buy-back at a similar
discount.
   New York-based Manufacturers Hanover Corp., the lead bank
of the Philippines' 12-bank creditor group, declined to
comment on Manila's desire for a second buy-back. But a
senior U.S. bank official said creditor banks would be likely
to participate in a second such arrangement.
   Whatever action is taken to reduce the country's total
debt and its payments burden, there is concern both in the
Philippines and among foreign bankers that the country may
need additional assistance. One reason is the earthquake that
struck northern Luzon on July 16, killing more than 1,600
people and causing some $800 million in damages.
   Another is the Mideast crisis, which is likely to take a
severe toll on the Philippines' balance-of-payments position,
especially if oil prices remain near $30 a barrel. The
country imports 65% of its energy needs, mostly in oil and
oil products. In addition, remittances from Philippine
workers in the Mideast are sure to decline.
   Before the earthquake and Iraq's Aug. 2 invasion of
Kuwait, the government estimated an overall
balance-of-payments deficit of $300 million for 1991. "It
almost certainly will be much higher than that," Mr. Cuisia
said, without providing a new estimate. In the first five
months of the year, the balance-of-payments deficit was $58
million.
   The Philippines will need new loans to help cover the
widening payments gap. Mr. Cuisia said the issue of new
lending was deferred during recent meetings with creditors
and will be taken up later this year.
   In the meantime, the National Economic Development Agency
has reduced its outlook for growth in gross national product
to 3.8% from 6.5% forecast at the beginning of the year.
   ---
   Peter Truell in Washington contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900830-0115
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900830-0115.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Pacific Southwest Corp.
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PSWC
</CO>
<LP>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. -- Pacific Southwest Corp. expects net
income for its fiscal year ended July 31 of between $800,000
and $950,000, or between 25 cents and 30 cents a share, on
$5.5 million of revenue.
   The financial services and real estate concern cited the
strong performance of its investment portfolio and the
receipt of certain notes payable in its fourth quarter. The
company posted a 1989 net loss of $71,000, or four cents a
share, on $2.8 million of revenue. Pacific Southwest shares
began trading yesterday in the national over-the-counter
market.
</LP>
