<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Werner Leaves
   ESPN to Head
   Prime Ventures
   ----
   By Dennis Kneale
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   CCB WNEWS TCOMA
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Roger L. Werner Jr. resigned as president and
chief executive officer of sports cable channel ESPN to head
Prime Ventures Inc., a regional sports network company newly
formed by cable executive Bill Daniels.
   Mr. Werner, 40 years old, was considered one of the most
promising young executives at Capital Cities/ABC Inc., which
runs ESPN and holds an 80% stake in the cable channel. A
successor will be named shortly, said Herb Granath, ESPN's
chairman and the president of ABC Video Enterprises. ESPN's
No. 2 executive, Steve Borenstein, may be the likely choice.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A former consultant with McKinsey &amp; Co. who had advised
ESPN in its early days, Mr. Werner joined the channel in 1980
as a vice president of finance and rose through several
promotions before jumping over to a sister unit, the ABC
television network, to become executive vice president there.
He returned to ESPN as its new president two years ago.
   Mr. Werner leaves ESPN a cable powerhouse, with 56 million
subscribing households and pretax earnings that topped $100
million last year. But the sports channel faces declining
profits this year because of expected losses of $20 million
or more on the first year of a new ESPN baseball contract,
and additional losses expected on a new football contract.
   ESPN officials said, however, the sports channel will post
ample profits this year, though earnings will be down from
1989 levels.
   Mr. Granath said Mr. Werner's departure was his own
choice. "We're very much chagrined to see him leaving, though
ESPN is in good shape," Mr. Granath said.
   Mr. Werner was lured to the new venture by Mr. Daniels,
the chairman of cable company Daniels &amp; Associates, with a
generous offer that Capital Cities/ABC couldn't afford to
match.
   "Bill Daniels made a sensational offer, and I decided to
take him up on it," Mr. Werner said yesterday in a telephone
news conference. He wouldn't reveal whether his new job
includes equity in the venture, but he said, "I do have a
substantial upside opportunity in growing the business. I
look forward to being an entrepreneur again."
   Prime Ventures Inc. will oversee a variety of
sports-oriented properties controlled or minority-owned by
Mr. Daniels. They include six regional sports networks owned
and operated by Daniels and Tele-Communications Inc., the
nation's largest cable operator.
   Mr. Werner's new post also will oversee a national sports
programming service called Prime Network; Prime Ticket
Netowrk, which operates in southern California and Hawaii and
is the nation's largest regional sports network; minority
interests in Home Sports Entertainment in Dallas and Houston
and regional sports channels elsewhere; and Daniels's
majority ownership of production company First Auto Sports
Television, and Denver Grand Prix Auto Race Inc.
</TEXT>
