<HL>
   Cotton Exchange
   Criticized by Agency
   For Fining a Trader
   ---
   Financial Instrument Unit
   Ignored Testimony, Says
   CFTC in Angry Opinion
   ----
   By Michael Siconolfi
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMODITY FUTURES TRADING COMMISSION (CFT)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- In a blistering opinion, the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission threw out a Cotton Exchange fine against a
futures trader for allegedly disruptive behavior.
   The problem?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It seems that the exchange's tiny Financial Instrument
Exchange division ignored testimony that the trader made an
offer -- not a bid -- in a disputed trade in the Finex's
dollar-index pit.
   No matter that the fine against the trader, Gary Fusfield,
was a mere $100. Said the CFTC in its harshly worded order:
"The magnitude of the exchange's error is not reduced by the
relatively trivial size of the fine."
   Futures exchanges increasingly have policed their pits for
abusive trading behavior following last year's federal probe
of futures trading practices at the two big Chicago
exchanges. But the Finex case is unusual because of the
exchange's apparent blunder -- and because the CFTC tossed
out the fine without remanding it to the exchange for further
review.
   "Because exchanges are under the gun to find violations,
it's become a bit of a numbers game," says Thomas Russo, a
New York lawyer who specializes in securities and commodities
law.
   The Finex declined to comment.
   The case stemmed from a disputed trade made by Mr.
Fusfield in March 1989. James Cahill, Finex floor committee
member, accused Mr. Fusfield of bidding -- or seeking to buy
futures contracts -- below Mr. Cahill's existing bid in the
dollar-index pit, and fined him $100. Such a low-ball bid
would have violated exchange rules.
   But in an affidavit filed with the exchange, Mr. Fusfield
insisted he made an offer -- to sell contracts -- at a price
slightly above the bid. Another witness in the pit verified
Mr. Fusfield's version of events.
   The Finex, however, ignored that testimony in issuing a
decision affirming the fine, the CFTC said.
   In its opinion, the CFTC called Finex's record of the
events "materially misleading," adding that its "reckless
disregard for an orderly and accurate procedure has made
review of its results impossible, and undermined confidence
in that result."
   In an unusual twist, the CFTC also refused to remand the
matter back to the Finex because it said the exchange's
disciplinary procedure was faulty.
   Mr. Fusfield, who termed the Finex review a "star-chamber
proceeding" in papers filed with the CFTC, said his
floor-brokerage business has folded. He now is a computer
consultant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900830-0015
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900830-0015.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Giving a Hand:
   These Hospital Children Take a Byte
   Out of Loneliness, Thanks to KidBits
   ----
   By John D. Williams
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   GTE
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   {From time to time in this column, The Wall Street Journal
will report on efforts by people in business to help others
in need.}
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sick children are among the toughest cases hospitals
handle. Scared, in pain and separated from home and parents,
young patients can get worse even though medicine says they
should get better. But thanks to 50 employees of a GTE Corp.
unit in Waltham, Mass., patients at Boston's Children's
Hospital now have an antidote to sick room blues: the
computer.
   Calling their project KidBits, the GTE Laboratories
employees have given about 10,000 hours of their own time
over the past three years to teach hospitalized children how
to use personal computers. The machines, donated by GTE, are
a therapeutic diversion for many hospitalized children, who
use them to play games, and a welcome communications tool for
those few youngsters whose illnesses or injuries confine them
to sterile isolation rooms.
   KidBits volunteers mostly help out on evenings or
weekends, though their employer lets them run quarterly
workday "computer fairs" for their young charges. "The GTE
people have made an outstanding contribution to our
department and to our patients and their families," says Myra
Fox, director of the hospital's patient activity department.
"They have extended themselves in a most unique volunteer
capacity."
   KidBits was started in 1987 by George Boggs, a GTE
research psychologist, after hearing of a friend's concern
for the morale of an 11-year-old nephew who had been in a
hospital isolation room for two months following a bone
marrow transplant.
   Mr. Boggs contacted hospital administrators, volunteering
to develop a computer-communications system for the young
patients. At first, the hospital staff was skeptical, citing
possible problems of patient safety, privacy and security.
But Mr. Boggs, who believes isolation slows a child patient's
recovery, persisted and won support from Ms. Fox.
   Although Mr. Boggs since has left GTE to join another
company, KidBits continues. There is, for example, Michael
Hackney, a 32-year-old chemist working on ceramics for auto
engines, who has averaged two hours a week over the past
three years teaching computer techniques to a total of 75
children. An easy-mannered and cheerful man, Mr. Hackney
instructs the children in such things as designing
computerized get-well cards for their other friends at the
hospital.
   KidBits' first installation was a voice system which
allowed children to dial up riddles on their hospital room
phone. Later, the KidBits volunteers trained 30 hospital
therapists to use the computers so that they, in turn, could
train the sick children. The GTE-sponsored computer fairs at
the hospital draw many of the KidBits volunteers. "You really
get something back when you see these sick kids giggling as
they help Snoopy escape the Red Baron on their computer
screens," says Rebecca Hudson, an active KidBit leader.
   But the most time-consuming project of the GTE crew has
been the development of a computer system that links a
network of four germ-free rooms to an activity room. This
system provides both communication and entertainment for the
young patients, who may have to stay in the isolated room for
six to 12 weeks. The first of these systems, eventually to be
installed in 13 rooms, began operation last month.
   David Fay, a GTE Labs psychologist, spent 15 evening hours
over a recent two-week span to help wire together the first
two rooms in the new system. "It makes me feel good to do
something with my professional skills {that has} a positive
impact on someone needing help," he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900830-0014
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900830-0014.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Reynolds Metals Co.:
   Aluminum Firm to Offer
   Non-Stick Microwave Wrap
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   RLM
</CO>
<IN>
HOUSEHOLD AND PERSONAL-CARE PRODUCTS (HHP)
</IN>
<LP>
   Reynolds Metals Co. said it will introduce a non-stick
microwave wrap.
   The Richmond, Va., aluminum company said the product,
which will be in stores in the Midwest next week, will be the
first paper food-wrap designed exclusively for microwave use.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Microwave cooking typically uses paper towels or waxed
paper, which tend to rip easily, or plastic wraps, which tend
to sag and stick to dishes and food in the microwave.
   First Brands Inc. came out with Glad Microwave Wrap, a
plastic-based wrap, but when it sagged under the oven's heat,
so did its sales.
   Reynolds says its product, a result of six years of
research, won't sag, tear, pick up grease or stick to food
and containers. "You can even cook cheese on it," says John
M. Lowrie, vice president of the company's consumer products
unit.
   Mr. Lowrie said the product, which will look like freezer
paper and have a coating of fatty acid, will be available
nationwide within a year. He predicts the wrap will have
sales of $20 million in its first year.
</TEXT>
