<HL>
   Commodities:
   Oil Prices Plunge on OPEC Pact to Lift Output,
   Perception That Mideast Tensions Are Easing
   ----
   By Caleb Solomon
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   HOUSTON -- Crude oil prices fell sharply following an OPEC
agreement to raise production and a growing perception among
market participants that Middle East tensions were easing.
   Ten of the 13 members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries agreed to raise output immediately to
help replace the four million barrels of oil taken off the
market because of the embargo of Iraqi and Kuwaiti petroleum.
Market estimates varied as to how much oil OPEC could quickly
put on the market.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil for October delivery fell $1.96 a barrel to
$25.92 on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the lowest level
in nearly three weeks. So far this week the contract has
dropped about $5 a barrel, or 16%, as financial markets
increasingly believe the chances for Mideast hostilities have
lessened.
   "The crude market weakened on perceptions of a moderating
Persian Gulf crisis," said Andrew Lebow, a crude oil analyst
with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc. He said a number
of news reports pointed to the "potential for a peaceful
solution."
   A number of traders said Iraq's promise to release women
and children held hostage, followed quickly by praise from
the U.S. government for the move, was one sign of easing
tensions. Market participants also pointed to reports that
Iraq had made behind-the-scenes peace overtures to the U.S.
   And in a market looking to go lower, even news that was
several days old was cited as a factor, such as the planned
meeting between the U.N. Secretary General and Iraq's foreign
minister, scheduled for today.
   Among OPEC members, the country that has sizable spare
capacity that could ratchet up production quickly is Saudi
Arabia. Traders were expecting that country to produce an
extra two million barrels a day, with enough output from
other OPEC nations to replace a total of three million to 3.5
million of the lost Iraqi and Kuwaiti production.
   But some reports on the New York Merc said Saudi Arabia
already was producing an extra two million barrels a day and
could produce one million beyond that by the end of the year,
for a total output as high as 8.5 million barrels daily. Some
people remained skeptical, however. "They've been working on
projects to upgrade production capacity, but 8.5 million is a
very high number," Mr. Lebow said.
   Gasoline prices also were off yesterday, in sympathy with
crude declines. Gasoline for September delivery finished at
84.72 cents a gallon, down 3.81.
   Heating oil fell sharply, with the September contract down
7.88 cents a gallon to 71.64 cents. A sharp buildup in
inventories reported Tuesday afternoon by the American
Petroleum Institute depressed prices. "Heating oil seems to
be in adequate supply right now," one trader said.
   In other commodity markets yesterday:
                                                                                                       

   GRAINS AND SOYBEANS: Prices of many corn, wheat and
soybean futures contracts sank for the third consecutive day
in the absence of any threatening developments in the Middle
East. Last week, grain prices rose on speculation that any
prolonged climb in oil prices would enable oil-producing
nations to import more U.S. grain. "The market is taking out
the war premium," said Victor Lespinasse, an assistant vice
president at Dean Witter Reynolds, Chicago. Crop prices are
also being depressed by good growing weather in the Midwest.
                                                                                                       

   SUGAR: Futures prices eased. The October contract was off
0.42 cent a pound at 11.05 cents and dropped at one point
below 11 cents. According to one analyst, the drop was a
delayed reaction to the softness that has hit many commodity
markets as fears of a war in the Middle East have eased.
There are no new developments concerning the current sugar
beet crop in Europe, the analyst said. Moderate but steady
demand for sugar in the world market from Mideast countries
has been curtailed by the crisis in that area, the analyst
said.
                                                                                                       

   ORANGE JUICE: Most futures contracts dropped their daily
permissible limits. Contract months from November forward
declined their daily limit of five cents a pound; November
ended at $1.5330. The soon-to-expire September contract,
which can rise or fall as much as 10 cents a pound from its
previous close, was down as much as eight cents a pound at
one point before partially recovering to end 5.95 cents lower
at $1.6345. Contributing to selling in the September contract
is the fact that Tuesday will be the first day on which
notices will be issued to deliver the concentrate against
September futures, an analyst said. Concentrate prices have
been under pressure because retail demand has slowed in the
face of price advances caused by damage to the Florida citrus
crop by last December's freeze. The lower prices might help
to revive some consumer demand, the analyst said. However,
supply concerns have been alleviated by a
better-than-expected crop this year in Florida and
expectations that new-crop Brazilian supplies will soon be
available, which could create further pressure on prices, the
analyst said.

   COCOA: Futures prices declined. The December contract was
off $31 a metric ton to $1,249. Analysts following
fundamentals said that rain in the Ivory Coast has eased
fears that recent dryness would hurt the crop, although one
analyst said the rains were light and scattered and weren't a
major factor. "The market fell back because there was little
reason for it to have advanced in the first place," she said.
John Gambino, a senior futures technical analyst for Merrill
Lynch, said that on a purely technical basis, the drop in the
December contract to $1,100 a ton in mid-August from $1,560
in May was simply a correction of the market's rally from
$960 to $1,560 between last December and May. Now, Mr.
Gambino said, "Prices may have bottomed out and could be
setting the stage for the renewal of the bull move." The
downward trend, he said, "fits into a classic three-wave
correction" that he now believes is complete. According to
that scenario, he said, the recent low of $1,100 "marks the
resumption of the bull market that began last December."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900830-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900830-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Bonds Rally on Strong Bidding at 5-Year Auction
   And Hints of Easing in Persian Gulf Tensions
   ----
   By Kevin Donovan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/30/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   MZ CHH NG VNCP SBK MNC JAPAN EUROP LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Bond prices rallied yesterday, boosted by
strong bidding at the Treasury's five-year note auction and
signs of less tension in the Mideast.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year note ended nearly 1 1/4
points higher, a gain of nearly $12.50 for a bond with a
$1,000 face amount. The issue's yield, which moves in the
opposite direction of its price, eased to 8.92% from 9.04% on
Tuesday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices opened modestly higher on news that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries agreed to raise
output levels. But a late-day rally in the Treasury futures
pit at the Chicago Board of Trade spilled over into the cash
market and pushed bond prices sharply higher.
   The futures market rally was sparked by the release of the
government's five-year note auction results, which were
better than some analysts had expected.
   The $8.56 billion of five-year, two-month notes fetched an
average yield of 8.57%. The yield was up from 8.54% at the
previous 5-year, 2-month note auction May 24 and was the
highest average yield at an auction since May 25, 1989, when
the average yield was 8.72%. In when-issued trading activity,
the yield on the five-year notes fell to 8.5%.
   The bid-to-cover ratio, which measures the number of bids
the Treasury receives for each bid it accepts, was a hefty
3.10-to-1, compared with 2.53-to-1 at the last five-year
auction.
   Noncompetitive bids, a gauge of individual investor
interest, were $672 million. That was up from $593 million at
the pervious five-year auction in May and the highest since
$696 million at the February 1989 five-year note auction.
   Those results seemed to indicate investors were warming
somewhat to fixed-income securities after weeks of sitting
frozen by fear of what the Middle East crisis would do to oil
prices and inflation.
   And news from and about the Mideast standoff suggested
conciliation was more a possibility than had been perceived.
   The Iraqi ambassador to the U.S. told reporters Iraq would
release all male foreigners, as well as women and children,
if the U.S. would assure it wouldn't attack Iraq.
   And an article in Newsday said that a purported
intermediary for Iraq made a secret offer to evacuate Kuwait
if it received guaranteed access to the Persian Gulf and
control of an oil field that dips into Kuwait, among other
conditions.
   Later in the day, the White House dismissed the proposal
and said it hadn't had any direct dealings with Iraq.
   "There were elements of constructiveness in the air and a
sense that investors don't have to build in a worst-case
scenario," said Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko
Securities Co. International Inc., New York.
   Fixed-income securities also were helped by the drop in
oil prices, which reflected the OPEC announcement. OPEC
nations, with Iran dissenting, agreed to boost production to
help make up for the embargo against crude from Iraq and
occupied Kuwait.
   The announcement sent oil prices tumbling. At the New York
Mercantile Exchange, crude oil for October delivery settled
at $25.92, down $1.96 from Tuesday.
   A drop in the Commodity Research Bureau's futures index
was also constructive to market tone. The CRB index settled
at 234.71, down 3.66 on the day, reflecting widespread price
declines in futures markets.
   Analysts said soybeans, corn and wheat futures all took a
tumble, as did orange juice, sugar, coffee and cocoa futures.
The grain futures led the declines, with some corn contracts
hitting life-of-contract lows.
   On the economic calendar for today is the weekly release
of initial unemployment claims at 8:30 a.m. EDT and the
release of July factory orders at 10 a.m. EDT.
   A Dow Jones Capital Markets Report consensus of economists
looks for an increase of 1.5% in factory orders after a 1.5%
decline in June.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   Treasury securities ended higher yesterday, after a rally
in the Treasury futures market spilled over into the cash
market.
   The benchmark 30-year bond ended at a price of 98 5/32 to
yield 8.92% compared with 96 30/32 to yield 9.04% on Tuesday.
The latest 10-year notes ended at 99 18/32 to yield 8.80%
compared with 98 26/32 to yield 8.91%.
   Short-term rates eased slightly yesterday. The discount
rate on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.47% for a
bond-equivalent yield of 7.70% while the rate on six-month
Treasury bills fell to 7.44% for a bond-equivalent yield of
7.82%.
   Here are details of yesterday's five-year, two-month note
auction:
                                                                                                       

   Rates are determined by the difference between the
purchase price and face value. Thus, higher bidding narrows
the investor's return while lower bidding widens it.
                                                                                                       

   Applications ..........................  $26,344,530,000
   Accepted bids .........................   $8,560,716,000
   Accepted at low price .................              20%
   Accepted noncompetitively .............     $672,000,000
   Average price (Rate) ..................   99.644 (8.57%)
   High price (Rate) .....................   99.685 (8.56%)
   Low price (Rate) ......................   99.603 (8.58%)
   Interest rate .........................           8 1/2%
                                                                                                       

   The notes are dated Sept. 4, 1990, and mature Nov. 15,
1995.
                                                                                                       

   Corporate Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Junk bonds ambled along in another day of uninspiring
summer trading.
   Prices of most go-go bonds, or top-quality, liquid
high-yield names, ended the session slightly higher, but junk
bonds from retailers and other cyclical issuers continued to
come under heavy selling pressure.
   Hard hit were junk bonds of R.H. Macy &amp; Co. and Carter
Hawley Hale Stores Inc. Macy's 14.50% senior subordinated
debentures slipped two points to 59 while the retailer's
14.50% subordinated debentures also slumped two points to end
at 46.
   Carter Hawley's 12.50% senior subordinated debentures slid
two points to 69 while the company's 12.25% senior
subordinated notes shed 1 1/2 points to end at 74.
   With recession looming, investors have been selling junk
bonds of retailers on fears that profits will be squeezed in
an economic downturn.
   Some other cyclical bonds that were hammered in
yesterday's trading: National Gypsum Co.'s 11.375% senior
subordinated notes, which fell two points to an offered price
of 43. Bids for the company's 14.50% senior subordinated
debentures tumbled four points to 36.
   Yesterday, Moody's Investors Service Inc. lowered the debt
ratings of National Gypsum because the decline in demand for
gypsum wallboard prices will continue to erode the company's
already skimpy interest coverage.
   In the investment-grade corporate debt market, high-grade
corporate bonds posted gains with long-term bonds advancing
as much as 3/4 point.
                                                                                                       

   Municipal Securities
                                                                                                       

   Municipal bond prices perked up after the doldrums of
recent weeks and wrapped up the calm session with gains of
1/4 to 1 1/2 points.
   New deals that came to the market this session were well
received, traders said.
   The top attraction was Puerto Rico's $350 million Public
Improvement Bonds of 1990.
   The general obligation bonds were priced by a Goldman,
Sachs &amp; Co. group to yield from 6.15% in 1991 to 7.735% in
2020.
   In secondary dealings, the New Jersey Turnpike Authority's
7.20% issues of 2018 ended 1 1/2 points higher at 98 1/2,
pushing the yield down to 7.31% from 7.44% at Tuesday's
close.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage- &amp; Asset-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   The asset-backed securities market reached another
milestone as nearly $26 billion of asset-backed issues have
been sold so far this year, exceeding the $24 billion sold in
all of 1989. This month alone, nearly $4 billion of
asset-backed securities have been issued.
   "We really expect asset-backed issuance to remain heavy,"
said Bruce Mahood, an analyst at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co.
   That's because issuers, especially banks, continue to step
up their sales while investors avidly seek the high-rated
securities that offer yields generally 0.55 to 0.90
percentage point higher than short-term Treasurys.
   With total issuance of $14 billion, sales of credit-card
securities dominate this year's asset-backed market and the
trend is expected to persist.
   But issuance of securities backed by auto loans may
slacken due to slow auto sales. Some automakers "aren't in
the market because their auto-loan portfolio has not grown
that spectacularly," said Michael Bassett, vice president at
Stone &amp; McCarthy Research Associates in Princeton, N.J.
   There are just two forthcoming asset-backed deals now
being mentioned repeatedly -- both credit-card issues. One is
a $300 million offering by Valley National Bank via J.P.
Morgan. Valley National is a unit of Phoenix, Ariz.-based
Valley National Corp. The other issue is $500 million Signet
Banking Corp. via Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. Signet is based in
Richmond, Va.
   Another name being bandied about is Baltimore-based MNC
Financial Inc., which is seen selling about $500 million of
credit-card securities later this quarter or early next
quarter.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   The Japanese bond market eroded further on continued talk
of an imminent hike in the official discount rate and a
weaker yen.
   Two Japanese national newspapers reported yesterday that
the Bank of Japan and the Ministry of Finance were
negotiating a discount rate hike. The reports, which were
denied by government officials, said the discount rate could
be raised as much as one full point as early as the beginning
of September. The rate, which is what the central bank
charges member banks for loans, now is 5.25%.
   Bank of Japan Governor Yasushi Mieno denied that the
central bank and the Finance Ministry were negotiating
another rate increase, but emphasized that the rise in the
price of oil was a new factor that the central bank was
carefully watching.
   Despite Mr. Mieno's denial, many dealers and analysts
believe there will be a discount rate increase by October.
   "I think they will hike the discount rate," says a dealer
at a major Japanese commercial bank. "They only have
September to do it in. If they don't {do it in September}
they will have missed the right time. . . . I think they are
deciding the scheduling."
   At the close of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the benchmark
No. 119 10-year government bond was quoted at a price of
82.18, down 0.55 point on the day, to yield 8.31%. (Foreign
bond yields are quoted here in local terms and therefore
differ somewhat from yields calculated for these markets by
U.S. investment firms, which tend to use the semiannual
compound measure to compare yields across markets. Using that
method, the yield on Japan's No. 119 bond ended at 7.61%,
according to Salomon Brothers Inc.)
   The discount rate was last raised in late March by a full
percentage point to 5.25%.
   In other markets:
   -- West German bond prices ended on a firmer tone despite
being faced with as much as 10 billion marks ($6.43 billion)
of fresh supply due for pricing in the next week.
   -- British government bonds ended little changed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
